H.2 verify (2026-05-14):

Scope: per-adapter hard timeout + per-row error isolation. A slow
       Composio response or a buggy adapter cannot block the other
       49 rows in a sweep. A throw BEFORE the existing adapter
       try/catch (e.g., a getAdapter regression) is caught by a new
       outer fence so the batch never sinks on a non-adapter bug.

Files landed:
  worker/cron-kicker/handler.ts        (MODIFIED — new
    ADAPTER_TIMEOUT_MS const (default 15s, env-overridable via
    POLL_ADAPTER_TIMEOUT_MS), PollTimeoutError class, withTimeout()
    helper with .finally(clearTimeout) cleanup and a fire-and-
    forget catch to suppress post-timeout unhandledRejections.
    adapter.poll() wrapped in withTimeout. Entire per-row body
    wrapped in an OUTER try/catch that catches anything the inner
    try didn't.)
  worker/cron-kicker/handler.test.ts   (MODIFIED — +3 tests for
    timeout / sync-throw / 5-row-batch-with-row-3-timeout.)

Static checks:
  ✓ pnpm -F @basics/worker exec vitest run cron-kicker/handler
        14/14 passing (3 new H.2 + 11 prior).
  ✓ pnpm -F @basics/worker exec vitest run (full worker suite)
        46 files / 540 passed / 19 skipped / 0 failures.
  ✓ pnpm -F @basics/worker exec tsc --noEmit  clean.

Behavior contract:
  ✓ Adapter calls bounded at ADAPTER_TIMEOUT_MS (15s default). On
    timeout: PollTimeoutError thrown, caught by the inner adapter
    try/catch, treated as one consecutive failure (exponential
    backoff applies). The remaining rows in the batch still
    process.
  ✓ Outer try/catch around the entire per-row body catches any
    error that escapes the inner try/catch (getAdapter throws,
    no-adapter UPDATE network blip, an unexpected refactor
    regression). Logs + counts as failed; the H.1 tentative lease
    keeps the row invisible for 5 min until a future sweep
    retries.
  ✓ Post-timeout: the adapter's promise continues until the
    underlying fetch settles. withTimeout's `.catch(() => undefined)`
    suppresses unhandledRejection if the promise eventually
    rejects. Memory/connection footprint of in-flight HTTP calls
    can accumulate under heavy timeout load — reviewer noted as a
    nit (fix would be threading an AbortSignal into adapter.poll).
  ✓ ADAPTER_TIMEOUT_MS is env-overridable for tests +
    emergency tuning.

Test specs:
  1. "H.2: adapter that times out → row failed within timeout
      window, sweep continues" — registered a stub adapter whose
      poll returns a Promise that never resolves. POLL_ADAPTER_
      TIMEOUT_MS=100ms forced. Asserts:
        - scanned=1, failed=1
        - whole sweep finishes within 500ms (real timer; tight
          assertion noted by reviewer as flake risk)
        - failure backoff UPDATE fired
  2. "H.2: adapter that throws synchronously → caught + row
      marked failed" — registered an adapter whose poll throws.
      Asserts scanned=1, failed=1.
  3. "H.2: 5-row batch with row-3 timeout → rows 1,2,4,5 still
      process; row-3 fails" — mixed batch with 4 fast adapters
      (resolve with empty newEvents) + 1 hanging adapter at
      index 2. Asserts:
        - scanned=5, failed=1
        - 5 total UPDATEs fired (4 success + 1 failure-backoff)
        - whole sweep finishes within 700ms with 80ms timeout

Adversarial review (review-1.json):
  Opus 4.7 via Agent tool; verdict: ship; 0 blockers; 5 nits.
  Nits:
    - withTimeout doesn't AbortSignal-cancel the in-flight request
    - Tight elapsed-time assertions vulnerable to CI flake (would
      benefit from vi.useFakeTimers or wider slack)
    - POLL_BATCH_SIZE × ADAPTER_TIMEOUT_MS = 50×15s = 750s worst-
      case sweep, exceeds 5-min Lambda ceiling if 21+ rows time
      out
    - Failure log doesn't distinguish timeout vs real adapter
      throw
    - p.catch(()=>undefined) is fire-and-forget; clearer with an
      explicit comment

Notes / decisions:
  - 15s default trade: most adapter calls finish in 300ms-3s;
    15s leaves headroom for a slow Composio HTTP round-trip
    while still capping worst-case impact. Operator can tune
    via POLL_ADAPTER_TIMEOUT_MS.
  - No AbortSignal threading yet — adapters' fetch calls don't
    accept signals today. Adding AbortSignal would require
    extending PollAdapterArgs + every adapter's fetch call.
    Deferred — current memory pressure from in-flight HTTP
    requests is minor at the F.10 scale.
  - The outer fence's catch increments `failed` but doesn't write
    a SQL UPDATE — the H.1 tentative lease keeps the row hidden
    for 5 min, after which a future sweep retries idempotently.
    If the outer catch could not write SQL (e.g., the pool is
    down), writing an UPDATE would just throw again.

Out of scope (lands in H.3+):
  - H.3: per-workspace fairness via ROW_NUMBER window
  - H.4: throughput — batch size 100 + Lambda self-invocation chain
  - H.5: per-workspace Composio rate-limit guard
  - H.6: Lambda memory bump + reservedConcurrency + EMF metrics
  - H.7: live load test (100 synthetic triggers)
